<subSubSection pageId="77" pageNumber="78" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="77.[151,1436,1689,2038]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">
Diagnosis: Large species. Surstyli bent ventrally and towards each other; epandrium asymmetrical, left side longer, cerci shifted to the right; SES appears to be divided, 20–22 hairs on each side; phallic guide sharply pointed, broadens before end. In lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[598,704,1761,1785]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="79.[151,250,1841,1864]" captionTargetBox="[286,1306,188,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-115@79.[258,1330,159,1834]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="FIGURE 26. Male genitalia of Eudorylas meruensis (A–F) and E. mikenensis (G–L).—A: outer surstylus with phallic guide, phallus and outer gonopod, lateral view, B: dorsal view, C: inner surstylus, lateral view, D: sperm pump with ejaculatory apodeme, E: surstyli, dorsal view, F: ventral view with phallic guide, phallus (without ST8), G: outer surstylus with phallic guide and outer gonopod, lateral view, H: dorsal view, I: inner surstylus with phallic guide and inner gonopod, lateral view, J: ventral view with phallus and phallic guide (without ST8), K: sperm pump with ejaculatory apodeme, L: surstyli, dorsal view. Scale bars: 0.1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6039237" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6039237/files/figure.png" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Fig. 26A</figureCitation>
) OS with a large process at the base above PG; phallus with supporting structure and a distinct, long process between PG and 
<collectingCountry box="[900,939,1798,1821]" name="Philippines" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">PH</collectingCountry>
; the trifid part of 
<collectingCountry box="[1144,1180,1798,1821]" name="Philippines" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">PH</collectingCountry>
seems to be separated from the rest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
